From 2b28548ca817c805cf45634fd7ac371598130c0c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Sun, 28 Jun 2026 08:44:19 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf #9-decompose: libsystem_kernel guest-side recvmsg-sleep
 accountant

The accountant for the generator hooks (darlingserver commit). Times each RPC
reply-wait per call number and dumps per process at exit, so a real build's 57%
recvmsg-sleep (perf #6) can be decomposed by call. OFF by default
(option DARLING_RPC_SLEEP_ACCOUNT) -> emulation builds byte-identical to baseline.

Design forced by this being the libc-free, below-libSystem RPC path:
 - timebase is rdtsc, NOT clock_gettime. A raw clock_gettime syscall between the RPC
   send and recv (inside the signal-blocked atomic region) wedges the guest -- launchd
   hangs forever in recvmsg. Bisected: stubbed bodies boot, table-write boots, the clock
   syscall is the sole trigger. rdtsc is a plain instruction (no syscall) -> safe. Unit
   is CPU ticks, directly comparable across calls for ranking.
 - start stamp is a STACK local threaded begin->end, NOT __thread (TLS aborts here
   pre-pthread: "pthread_t was corrupted").
 - dumped from the clean exit path (sys_exit -> __darling_rpc_sleep_dump), NOT a
   destructor: dyld rejects initializers/terminators in this below-libSystem image
   ("initializer in image ... that does not link with libSystem.dylib").
 - the table + dump live in a single .c compiled ONCE into the emulation lib, with the
   header providing only inline begin/end over an extern table. The generated rpc.c is
   compiled into BOTH emulation and emulation_dyld; a header-static table would split in
   two -> the running wrappers fill one while the dump reads the other (observed: dumps
   fired but every table was empty). One shared definition fixes it.

Validated: ON build boots + real make -j8 300/300, dumps a clean per-callnum breakdown
(mach_msg_overwrite 19%, kprintf 14.5%, fork_wait_for_child 12.6%, ...). OFF build boots
clean with zero diagnostic output and no diagnostic strings/symbols in the dylib.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
